      "Local negotiation and administrative transaction costs (per-settlement, case-by-case maintainer discussions)"
    ],
    "equity_impact": "Likely reduces short-term travel-burden inequity for lower-SES and Roma families who currently benefit from local schooling, but this rests on weak evidence and untested assumptions about which families remain versus exit under 'white flight' dynamics documented elsewhere in the Hungarian system; without transparent enrollment thresholds or transport-cost data, the scenario cannot guarantee that the poorest villages retain viable multigrade staffing rather than drifting into de facto under-resourced status.",
    "evidence_status": "moderate",
    "expected_benefits": [
      "Preserves the school's documented community-hub and place-identity function without requiring new legal or institutional structures.",
      "Avoids abrupt travel-burden increases for families, since children continue attending the local school rather than being reassigned under mandatory catchment rules.",
      "Requires minimal upfront legal or administrative change, since multigrade classrooms and felmenő rendszer mechanisms are already codified and operational."
