    "goal": "Keep the existing municipal/state-maintained village school open as long as feasible, relying on multigrade classrooms, felmenő rendszer phase-out and ad hoc local negotiation without a national framework.",
    "implementation_steps": [
      {
        "action": "Undertake extended in-service multigrade-pedagogy training with realistic multi-year lead time, recognizing that upskilling sufficient teachers for quality multigrade instruction requires longer preparation than a single cycle.",
        "actor": "School leaders and teaching staff",
        "timeline": "year 1-4, recurring"
      },
      {
        "action": "Negotiate transparent, documented retention arrangements including enrollment and cost data disclosure to parents and local council.",
        "actor": "Tankerület (district center) and municipality",
        "timeline": "year 1-2, ongoing"
      },
      {
        "action": "Clarify whether pre-2010 independent expert assessment requirements before closure remain in force, to standardize procedural protections.",
        "actor": "Ministry/EMMI",
        "timeline": "year 1"
      }
    ],
    "legacy_scenario_id": "S1",
    "mechanisms": [
      "Hungarian law already provides an administratively ready alternative to closure: multigrade (összevont) classrooms combining up to three (exceptionally four) consecutive grades, used in an estimated 200-300 schools nationally.",
      "OFI research concludes that rural small-school pupil outcomes are broadly comparable to larger village schools and only moderately below urban schools once family socioeconomic background is controlled for, undermining pure efficiency arguments for closure.",
      "The felmenő rendszer (grade-by-grade phase-in mechanism) is applied in practice to school reorganization to protect currently-enrolled student cohorts from mid-course disruption, with documented 2025 cases implementing closure-related splits across multiple school years.",
      "Small schools (under 150 pupils) comprise nearly one-third of municipal primary schools yet enroll fewer than 10% of all students, and researchers argue the cost differential alone does not constitute a serious system-wide efficiency problem."
    ],
    "risks": [
      "Chronic under-budgeting of the district (tankerület) system creates persistent fiscal pressure to consolidate regardless of stated 'protect as long as there is demand' policy, risking quiet erosion rather than open confrontation.",
      "Absence of a bright-line statutory threshold leaves retention decisions to discretionary tankerület judgment, which is politically reversible year to year and vulnerable to administration change."
    ],
    "title": "Status quo plus incremental adaptation",
